03950nam a22006135i 9780292798984DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212000txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927989847 a10.7560/7774462doi  a(DE-B1597)587446  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aSigal, Pete, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Moon Goddesses to Virgins :bThe Colonization of Yucatecan Maya Sexual Desire /cPete Sigal. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE AND ACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES ON TRANSCRIPTION AND TRANSLATION -- tONE Searching for the Moon Goddess -- tTWO Religion and Family -- tTHREE Framing Maya Sexual Desire -- tFOUR Fornicating with Priests, Communicating with Gods -- tFIVE The Unvirgin Virgin -- tSIX Gender, Lineage, and the Blood of the Rulers -- tSEVEN Blood, Semen, and Ritual -- tEIGHT Transsexuality and the Floating Phallus -- tNINE Ritualized Bisexuality -- tTEN Finding the Virgin Mary -- tNOTES -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the preconquest Maya, sexuality was a part of ritual discourse and performance, and all sex acts were understood in terms of their power to create, maintain, and destroy society. As postconquest Maya adapted to life under colonial rule, they neither fully abandoned these views nor completely adopted the formulation of sexuality prescribed by Spanish Catholicism. Instead, they evolved hybridized notions of sexual desire, represented in the figure of the Virgin Mary as a sexual goddess, whose sex acts embodied both creative and destructive components. This highly innovative book decodes the process through which this colonization of Yucatan Maya sexual desire occurred. Pete Sigal frames the discussion around a series of texts, including the Books of Chilam Balam and the Ritual of the Bacabs, that were written by seventeenth and eighteenth century Maya nobles to elucidate the history, religion, and philosophy of the Yucatecan Maya communities. Drawing on the insights of philology, discourse analysis, and deconstruction, he analyzes the sexual fantasies, fears, and desires that are presented, often unintentionally, in the "margins" of these texts and shows how they illuminate issues of colonialism, power, ritual, and gender.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMayasxSexual behaviorzMexicozYucatán (State). 0aMayaszMexicozYucatán (State)xPsychology. 0aMayaszMexicozYucatán (State)xReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77744640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798984/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK